; tech book found in subway
INUMBER 894
NAME 384
WEIGHT 5
VOLUME 5
INTERIOR 2
OPENABLE
CONTAINER ON
ARTICLE THE
;
CALL 33
*DESCRIPTION_START
This book is actually a plastic covered binder, black. Inside, the pages
are actually individual sheets of paper specially coated to protect them
from getting destroyed.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB LOOK -1
 IFVAR INTNUM3 = 1
   ECHO PLAYER *** THIS BOOK IS MEANT FOR THE
   ECHO PLAYER     TECHNOLOGISTS AS A ROLE
   ECHO PLAYER     PLAYING DEVICE. DO NOT USE   ***%c
 ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB OPEN -1
    IFVAR ITEMBIT1 = 0
      EQUAL ITEMVAL1 1 ;?
      EQUAL ITEMBIT1 1 ;           *** BOOK OPEN ***
      ECHO PLAYER You open %a to the first page.
      ECHO OTHERS %n opens %a and turns to the first page.
      CLEARVERB
    ELSE
      ECHO PLAYER %a is already open.
      CLEARVERB
    ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB CLOSE -1
     IFVAR ITEMBIT1 = 1
       EQUAL ITEMBIT1 0 ; book closed
       ECHO PLAYER You close %a.
       ECHO OTHERS %n closes %a.
       CLEARVERB
     ELSE
       ECHO PLAYER %a is already closed.
       CLEARVERB
     ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB READ -1
  IFVAR ITEMBIT1 = 1
      IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 1
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO OTHERS %n pores over the %a.
         ECHO PLAYER                                                   Page 1%c
         ECHO PLAYER Intorudction to Subways: An overview.%c
         ECHO PLAYER The subway system is one of the most important and efficient transpor-
         ECHO PLAYER tation systems in use in a modern society. It allows for large
         ECHO PLAYER scale cities to remove the problems of traffic conjestion and
         ECHO PLAYER pollution, while at the same time providing a safe, easy to use
         ECHO PLAYER means of travel. For a subway to be effective, it must run on time,
         ECHO PLAYER be in good condition, accessible to all (ie, many accesses) and
         ECHO PLAYER affordable.
         ECHO PLAYER %cThe subway system is a below surface transportation system of
         ECHO PLAYER single or multiple vehicles connected, and run via a rail system.
         ECHO PLAYER Power is supplied through either overhead lines, or through the
         ECHO PLAYER the rails themselves. At one point in the subway's history, operators
         ECHO PLAYER were needed to control the trains themsevles, but with the development
         ECHO PLAYER advanced remote servo-control systems (RSCS), human operators were
         ECHO PLAYER slowly phased out. Central computers contol the arrival and departure
         ECHO PLAYER times of trains from stations, and regulate speeds and directional
         ECHO PLAYER control while en route. The system, having been perfected over the
         ECHO PLAYER the last decade, is now in wide use.
         ECHO PLAYER %cThe remainder of this manual is devoted to the maintenance and
         ECHO PLAYER programming of the subway control systems.
      ENDIF

      IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 2
         IFVAR INTNUM55 ! 2
           EQUAL INTNUM55 2
           ADD INTNUM68 5
           STRCVT 0 INTNUM68
           GMMSG ** %n's intnum68 = %0.
         ENDIF
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO OTHERS %n pores over the %a.
         ECHO PLAYER                                                   Page 2%c
         ECHO PLAYER Maintenance of Subway cars.%c
         ECHO PLAYER There are four basic steps to maintaining a subway car in prime working
         ECHO PLAYER condition. The four parts of the Subway are, the axles, the doors, the
         ECHO PLAYER servo-motor and the RSCS. Each chapter will discuss the basics of
         ECHO PLAYER maintaining and troubleshooting problems with each.%c
      ENDIF

      IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 3
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO OTHERS %n pores over the %a.
         ECHO PLAYER                                                   Page 3%c
         ECHO PLAYER Chapter 1: Subway Axles, and other mechanical systems.%c
         ECHO PLAYER A subway car rests on two axles, connected to two sets of four wheels
         ECHO PLAYER on both sides of the car itself. The axle must be in good condition,
         ECHO PLAYER free to turn, properly lubed and firmly connected to the bell housing
         ECHO PLAYER of the servo motor which will supply the torque necessary to move
         ECHO PLAYER the car.
         ECHO PLAYER Each one of the two axles connects to a servo motor, and thus is
         ECHO PLAYER supplied with torque. A safety factor of two was designed into the
         ECHO PLAYER the subway motor systems, so techincally, a subway could run on just
         ECHO PLAYER axle. However, this is not recomended except in emergencies.
      ENDIF

      IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 4
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO OTHERS %n pores over the %a.
         ECHO PLAYER                                                   Page 4%c
         ECHO PLAYER Chapter 2: Subway doors. The doors are another important part of
         ECHO PLAYER the subway car itself, providing access to the platforms from the
         ECHO PLAYER cars and the cars from the platforms. The doors work on a rack and
         ECHO PLAYER pinion design and hooked to remote systems on the platform. When
         ECHO PLAYER the doors are aligned with the point on the platform, a sensor is
         ECHO PLAYER tripped and the gears are engaged to open the door. A timing delay
         ECHO PLAYER is set and if nothing is blocking the door, they will close at the
         ECHO PLAYER conclusion of the delay. The subway car can not engage it's drive
         ECHO PLAYER system until all doors are closed.
         ECHO PLAYER To access the gears and servos connected to the door, an access panel
         ECHO PLAYER is situated near the base at the point the door recesses.
      ENDIF

      IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 5
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO OTHERS %n pores over the %a.
         ECHO PLAYER                                                   Page 5%c
         ECHO PLAYER Chapter 3: The servo motor. The servo motor is the mechanical engine
         ECHO PLAYER that drives the subway car. The servo motor employs simple electric-to
         ECHO PLAYER kinetic energy system. Once electrical power is supplied, the servos
         ECHO PLAYER will turn the axles. A resistor is used to regulate speed. Ensuring
         ECHO PLAYER that the motor is dry, and all of the leads are clean and properly
         ECHO PLAYER connected is important for a long lasting motor. The servo motors
         ECHO PLAYER rest under the car, down the long axis, close to the axles.
       ENDIF

       IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 6
        IFVAR INTNUM55 ! 2
          ADD INTNUM68 5
          EQUAL INTNUM55 2
          STRCVT 0 INTNUM68
          GMMSG  ** %n's INTNUM68 = %0.
        ENDIF
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO OTHERS %n pores over the %a.
         ECHO PLAYER                                                   Page 6%c
         ECHO PLAYER Chapter 4: The RSCS. The RSCS is basically a remote computer
         ECHO PLAYER which allows a central operator to monitor and route trains
         ECHO PLAYER along predesigned paths at preset time intervals.
         ECHO PLAYER The programming station for the RSCS can be found in the control
         ECHO PLAYER room of the main terminus. Each substation will have a monitoring
         ECHO PLAYER system.
       ENDIF
  ELSE
    ECHO PLAYER %a is closed.
    CLEARVERB
  ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB TURN -1
 IFVAR ITEMBIT1 = 1
     CLEARVERB
     ADD ITEMVAL1 1
     IFVAR ITEMVAL1 > 4
       EQUAL ITEMVAL1 1
       STRCVT 0 ITEMVAL1
       ECHO PLAYER You turn %a to page %0.
       ECHO OTHERS %n turns a page of %a.
       CLEARVERB
     ELSE
       STRCVT 0 ITEMVAL1
       ECHO PLAYER You turn %a to page %0.
       ECHO OTHERS %n turns a page of %a.
       CLEARVERB
     ENDIF
 ELSE
   ECHO PLAYER The book is closed.
   CLEARVERB
 ENDIF
ENDIF

